07486nam a22010335i 9780812291360DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013957206  a(OCoLC)1029823032  a(OCoLC)1032693788  a(OCoLC)1037980110  a(OCoLC)1041973580  a(OCoLC)1046607164  a(OCoLC)1047015714  a(OCoLC)979724822  a97808122913607 a10.9783/97808122913602doi  a(DE-B1597)452747  a(OCoLC)915912551  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJK1965b.A48 2015 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a324.97322300aAmerica at the Ballot Box :bElections and Political History /ced. by Gareth Davies, Julian E. Zelizer. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b5 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Culture in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Devolution of 1800: Jefferson’s Election and the Birth of American Government -- t2. The Bombshell of 1844 -- t3. Beyond the Realignment Synthesis: Th e 1860 Election Reconsidered -- t4. Markets, Morality, and the Media: The Election of 1884 and the Iconography of Progressivism -- t5. Anglophobia in Nineteenth- Century Elections, Politics, and Diplomacy -- t6. The War and Peace Election of 1916 -- t7. Farewell to the “Smoke- Filled Room”: Parties, Interests, Public Relations, and the Election of 1924 -- t8. The New Deal in 1940: Embattled or Entrenched? -- t9. “Why Don’t You Just Get an Actor?”: Th e Advent of Television in the 1952 Campaign -- t10. Giving Liberalism a Window: Th e 1964 Election -- t11. The 1980 Election: Victory Without Success -- t12. Beyond the Water’s Edge: Foreign Policy and Electoral Politics -- t13. From Corn to Caviar: Th e Evolution of Presidential Election Communications, 1960–2000 -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aElections are, and always have been, the lifeblood of American democracy. Often raucous and sharply contentious, sometimes featuring grand debates about the nation's future, and invariably full of dramatic moments, elections offer insight into the character and historical evolution of American politics. America at the Ballot Box uses the history of presidential elections to illuminate American political democracy and its development from the early Republic to the late twentieth century.Some of the contributions in America at the Ballot Box focus on elections that resulted in dramatic political change, including Jefferson's defeat of Adams in 1800, the 1860 election of Lincoln, and Reagan's 1980 landslide victory. Others concentrate on contests whose importance lies more in the way they illuminate the broad, underlying processes of political change, such as the corruption controversy of Cleveland's acrimonious election in 1884 or the advent of television advertising during the 1952 campaign, when Eisenhower defeated Stevenson. Another set of essays takes a thematic approach, exploring the impact of foreign relations, Anglophobia, and political communications over long periods of electoral time. Uniting all of the chapters is the common conviction that elections provide a unique vantage point from which to view the American political system.Ranging from landmark contests to less influential victories and defeats, the essays by leading political historians seek to rehabilitate the historical significance of presidential elections and integrate them into the broader evolution of American government, policies, and politics.Contributors: Brian Balogh, Gareth Davies, Meg Jacobs, Richard R. John, Kevin M. Kruse, Jeffrey L. Pasley, Andrew Preston, Elizabeth Sanders, Bruce J. Schulman, Jay Sexton, Adam I. P. Smith, Sean Wilentz, Julian E. Zelizer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Eng